{"parse":{"title":"sol","pageid":3902,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Sol|Appendix:Variations of \"sol\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''Sol'''os}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{was wotd|2021|June|17}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom Glover's [[solmization]], from {{inh|en|enm|sol||fifth degree or note of Guido of Arezzo's hexachordal scales}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|pos=''n.''(2)|noformat=1|id=MED41379}}</ref> {{der|en|it|sol}} in the solmization of Guido of Arezzo, from the first syllable of {{der|en|la|solve|t=wash away}} in the lyrics of the scale-ascending hymn ''{{w|Ut queant laxis}}'' by Paulus Deacon.<ref>Compare {{R:OED Online|pos=''n.''{{sup|2}}|noformat=1|id=184023|date=December 2020|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|alt=sol{{sup|1}}|pos=n}}</ref>\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/sɒl/|/səʊl/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-I learned some phrases-sol.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{enPR|sōl|a=GA}}, {{IPA|en|/sɔl/|/sɑl/|/soʊl/}}\n* {{homophones|en|soul|sole}} {{q|Canada|US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒl|əʊl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|solfege}}{{lb|en|music}}\n## In a [[movable#Adjective|movable]]-[[do]] or [[tonic#Adjective|tonic]] [[sol-fa]] [[system]]: the [[fifth]] [[step#Noun|step]] in a [[scale#Noun|scale]], [[precede]]d by [[fa]] and [[follow]]ed by [[la]].\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Taming of the Shrew|act=III|scene=i|page=218|column=2|passage=''D '''ſol''' re'', one [[clef|Cliffe]], two notes haue I, / ''Ela mi'', ſhow pitty or I die.}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Romeo and Juliet Q1-2|act=IV|scene=v|page=69|passage=''Ser''[''vant'', ''i.e.'', Peter]. Alack alack what ſhal I doe, come Fidlers play me ſome mery dumpe. / ''I.'' [''First musician'']. A ſir, this is no time to play. / {{...}} / ''Ser.'' Then will I giue it you, and ſoundly to. / ''I.'' What will you giue vs? / ''Ser.'' The fidler, Ile re you, Ile fa you, Ile '''ſol''' you. / ''I.'' If you re vs and fa vs, we will note you.|footer=A {{glossary|nonce}} use as a verb.|brackets=on}}\n## In a [[fixed#Adjective|fixed]]-do system: the [[musical#Adjective|musical]] [[note#Noun|note]] [[G]].\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{l|en|so}}\n* {{l|en|soh}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|in a movable-do system: the fifth step in a scale}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Arabic: {{tt|ar|سُول|m}}, {{tt|ar|سُول|tr=sol|m}}\n* Basque: {{tt+|eu|sol}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|сол}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|sol|m}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|sol|m}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|sol}}, {{tt+|fi|so}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|sol|m}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|sol|m}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|σολ|n}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|szó|id=solfege-5}}\n* Japanese: {{tt|ja|ソル|tr=soru}}, {{tt+|ja|ソ|tr=so}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|솔}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt+|mk|сол|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|sol|m}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|sol|m}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|соль|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|sol|m}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|son}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|in a fixed-do system: the musical note G}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*solh₂-}}\n{{dercat|en|itc-pro}}\n{{lbor|en|fro|sol||French coin}} (modern {{cog|fr|sou}}), from {{der|en|la|solidum}}, the {{glossary|accusative}} {{glossary|singular}} of {{m|la|solidus||Roman gold coin; (''adjective'') solid}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''n.''{{sup|3}}|noformat=1|id=184024|date=December 2020}}</ref> {{doublet|en|sold|soldo|solid|solidus|sou|xu}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/sɒl/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-I learned some phrases-sol.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/sɔl/|/sɑl/|a=GA}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|historical}} An [[old]] [[coin#Noun|coin]] from [[France]] and some other [[country|countries]] [[worth#Adjective|worth]] 12 [[denier]]s.\n#* {{RQ:Jonson Volpone|year=1616|act=IV|scene=v|pages=502–503|pageref=503|passage=This fellow, For ſix '''ſols''' more, would pleade againſt his Maker.}}\n#* {{RQ:Coryat Crudities|chapter=My Obseruations of the Most Glorious, Peerelesse, and Mayden Citie of Venice:{{nb...|I Call It Mayden because It was Neuer Conquered.}}|page=285|lines=18–24|passage=Moſt of their owne coines that I ſaw were theſe. In gold but one, which is their chiquiney: This piece doth much vary in the value. For ſometimes it is high, ſometimes low. When I was there, a chiquiney was worth eleuen liuers, and twelue '''ſols'''. Which counteruaileth eight ſhillings and eight pence halfe penny of our money.}}\n#* {{RQ:Smollett Roderick Random|volume=II|chapter=XLIV|page=69|passage=It was the fate of the grenadier company, to which I now belonged, to lie at Rheims, where I found myſelf in the utmoſt want of every thing: My pay, which amounted to five '''ſols''' a day, far from ſupplying me with neceſſaries; being ſcarce ſufficient to procure a wretched ſubſiſtance, to keep ſoul and body together; {{...}}}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|solid}}\n* {{l|en|solidus}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|old coin from France and other countries}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{PIE word|en|sóh₂wl̥}}\nFrom {{bor|en|es|sol||sun}},<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''n.''{{sup|5}}|noformat=1|id=184026|date=June 2018|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|alt=sol{{sup|3}}|pos=n}}</ref> from {{der|en|la|sol|sōl|sun}}, ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥||sun}}. {{doublet|en|Sol|[[sol#Etymology 4|sol]]}}, directly from the Latin.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/sɒl/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-I learned some phrases-sol.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/sɔl/|/sɑl/|a=GA}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|+|es}}\n\n# {{lb|en|historical}} A [[former]] [[Spanish America|Spanish-American]] [[silver#Adjective|silver]] [[coin#Noun|coin]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Antoine-Simon Le Page du Pratz|[Antoine-Simon] Le Page du Pratz]]|chapter=Of the Commerce that Is, and May Be, Carried Out in ''Louisiana''.{{nb...|Of the Commodities which that Province may Furnish in Return for Those of Europe. Of the Commerce of Louisiana with the Isles.}}|translator=[anonymous]|title=The History of Louisiana, or of the Western Parts of Virginia and Carolina:{{nb...|Containing a Description of Countries that Lye on Both Sides of the River Missisipi: With an Account of the Settlements, Inhabitants, Soil, Climate, and Products. Translated from the French, (Lately Published,) by M. Le Page Du Pratz; with Some Notes and Observations Relating to Our Colonies. In Two Volumes.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} T. Becket and P. A. De Hondt{{nb...|in the Strand.}}|year=1763|volume=I|page=336|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/cihm_18172/page/n415/mode/1up|oclc=85253444|passage=The ''Tobacco'' of this colony is ſo excellent, that if the commerce thereof was free, it would ſell for one hundred '''ſols''' and ſix livres the pound, ſo fine and delicate is its juice and flavour.}}\n# ''In full'' '''[[nuevo sol]]''' ''or'' '''new sol''': the [[main#Adjective|main]] [[currency]] [[unit]] of [[Peru]] which replaced the [[inti]] in 1991; also, a coin of this [[value#Noun|value]].\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|Sun}}, {{l|en|sun}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|Spanish-American silver coin}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|main currency unit of Peru}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|索爾}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom {{bor|en|la|sol|sōl|sun}};<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''n.''{{sup|7}}|noformat=1|id=184028|date=March 2018}}</ref> see further at [[#Etymology 3|etymology 3]]. {{doublet|en|[[sol#Etymology 3|sol]]}} from Spanish.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/sɒl/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-I learned some phrases-sol.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/sɔl/|/sɑl/|a=GA}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|day}}{{lb|en|astronomy}} A [[solar day]] on the [[planet]] [[Mars]] ([[equivalent]] to 24 [[hour]]s, 39 [[minute#Noun|minutes]], 35 [[second#Noun|seconds]]).\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Andy Weir|chapter=3|title=[[w:The Martian (Weir novel)|The Martian]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Broadway Books|year=2011|year_published=2014|page=18|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/martiannovel0000weir/page/18/mode/1up|isbn=978-1-101-90358-2|passage=I need to create calories. And I need enough to last the 1387 '''sols''' until Ares 4 arrives. If I don't get rescued by Ares 4, I'm dead anyway. A '''sol''' is 39 minutes longer than a day, so it works out to be 1425 days. That's my target: 1425 days of food.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Gerard 't Hooft|Gerard ’t Hooft]]; Stefan Vandoren|chapter=10⁵ Seconds = 100,000 Seconds = 1.16 days = 27.78 Hours|translator=Saskia A. Eisberg-’t Hooft|title=Time in Powers of Ten: Natural Phenomena and Their Timescales|location=Singapore|publisher=[[w:World Scientific|World Scientific Publishing Co.]]|year=2014|section=part I|page=25|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=PZu6CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|isbn=978-981-4489-80-5|passage=88,775 seconds = 24 hours, 39 minutes and 35 seconds / The duration of a synodic day on Mars, a ‘'''sol'''’}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2023|author=Katie L. Carroll|title=Selfies From Mars: The True Story of Mars Rover Opportunity|page=2\n|passage=On '''sol''' 46 (March 11, 2004 on Earth), Opportunity gathered data on a cluster of [[blueberry|blueberries]] and confirmed the team's suspicions that this area of Mars once contained liquid water.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|tosol}}\n* {{l|en|yestersol}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|Sol}}\n* {{l|en|Sun}}, {{l|en|sun}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|solar day on the planet Mars}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|火星日}}\n* Finnish: {{tt|fi|[[Mars|Marsin]] [[päivä]]}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt|no|marsdøgn|n|n-p}}\n* Russian: {{tt|ru|[[марсианский|марсиа́нские]] [[су́тки]]|f-p}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n{{etymon|en|id=solution|solution}}\nSense 1 (“type of colloid”) is derived from {{m|en|-sol}} (in words like {{m|en|alcosol}} and {{m|en|hydrosol}}), an {{abbrev|en|solution|nocap=1}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''n.''{{sup|6}}|noformat=1|id=184027|date=September 2018|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|alt=sol{{sup|2}}|pos=n}}</ref>\n\nSense 2 (“solution to an objection”) is derived directly from {{m|en|solution}}.<ref>{{R:OED Online|entry=† sol|pos=''n.''{{sup|4}}|noformat=1|id=184025|date=March 2021}}</ref>\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/sɒl/|a=RP}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-I learned some phrases-sol.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/sɔl/|/sɑl/|a=GA}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɒl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{sid|en|colloid}} {{lb|en|physical chemistry}} A [[type#Noun|type]] of [[colloid#Noun|colloid]] in which a [[solid#Noun|solid]] is [[disperse]]d in a [[liquid#Noun|liquid]].\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[solution]] to an [[objection]] (or \"[[ob]]\"), for example, in [[controversial]] [[divinity]].\n#* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy|edition=2nd|chapter=Symptomes Generall, Loue to Their Owne Sect, Hate of All Other Religions,{{nb...|Obstinacie, Peevishnesse, Ready to Vndergoe any Danger or Crosse for It, Martyrs, Blind Zeale, Blinde Obedience, Fastings, Vowes, Beliefe of Incredibilities, Impossibilities: Particular of Gentiles, Mahometans, Iewes, Christians, and in Them Heretikes Old and New, Schismatickes, Schoolemen, Prophets, Enthusiasts, &c.}}|partition=3|section=4|member=1|subsection=3|page=524|url=https://archive.org/details/2319035R.nlm.nih.gov/page/n623/mode/1up|passage=[F]or that they had nothing elſe to doe, {{...}} haue coyned a thouſand idle queſtions, nice diſtinctions, Obs and '''Sols''', {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Butler Hudibras|year=1905|part=3|canto=II|page=165|passage=Where ''Hinderſon, and th' other Maſſes'' / ''Were ſent to Cap Texts, and Put Caſes'': / To paſs for deep, and ''Learned Scholars'', / Although but Paltry, ''Ob-and-'''Sol'''lers'':{{nb...}}|brackets=on}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|cytosol|organosol|plastisol|pyrosol|sonosol\n|aerosol|sol-gel|solate|solation|solid sol}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|type of colloid in which a solid is dispersed in a liquid}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Bulgarian: {{tt|bg|зол|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|sol|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|溶膠}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|sooli}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|sol|m}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|sol|m}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Sol|n}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|szol}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|ゾル|tr=zoru}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|zol|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|sol|m}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|sol|n}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|золь|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|сол}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|sol}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|sol|m}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt|tl|maladigkiting kaluswan}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 6===\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|?}}\n\n# {{lb|en|informal|labour|leftism}} {{clipping of|en|solidarity}}.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Used with {{m|en|in}} as an informal written [[valediction]].\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=los|LOS|OLS|SLO|los'}}\n\n{{cln|en|heteronyms}}\n{{C|en|Coins|Currencies|Historical currencies|History of France|Mars (planet)|Peru}}\n\n==Aragonese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{an-pr}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|an|la|sol|sōl|sun}}, ultimately from {{inh|an|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{an-noun|m}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n# [[sunlight]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{an-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (musical note)\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:an:Aragonario|es=sol}}\n* 2022 October, ''Diccionario ortografico de l'aragonés (Seguntes la PO de l'EFA)'' (version 13) (in Aragonese), [http://www.academiadelaragones.org/biblio/Edacar13.pdf#page=2187 page 2187]\n* 2024 October, ''Diccionario aragonés-castellano-catalán: Estudio de Filología Aragonesa'' (version 14) (in Aragonese), [http://www.academiadelaragones.org/biblio/EDACAR14DACC.pdf#page=1045 page 1045]\n\n==Asturian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom a contraction of the preposition {{m|ast|so||under}} + masculine singular article {{m|ast|el||the}}.\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|ast|contraction|g=m}}\n\n# (West) [[under]] [[the]]\n# (Center and East) [[on]] [[the]]\n\n==Azerbaijani==\n{{az-variant|сол|سوْل}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|az|trk-pro|*sōl}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|az|[soɫ]}}\n* {{audio|az|LL-Q9292 (aze)-Azerbaijani audiorecordings-sol.wav|a=Baku}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{az-noun}}\n\n# [[left]]\n#: {{uxi|az|küçənin '''sol '''tərəfi|'''left '''side of the street}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{az-decl-noun|o|c}}\n\n====Antonyms====\n* {{l|az|sağ}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|az|solaxay||[[left-hander]]}}\n* {{l|az|solçu||[[leftist]]}}\n** {{l|az|solçuluq||[[leftism]]}}\n\n{{C|az|Directions}}\n\n==Bislama==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|bi|en|salt}}. Cognate with {{cog|tpi|sol}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|bi|/ˈsol/}}\n* {{hyph|bi|sol}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|bi|nouns}}\n\n# [[salt]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|bi\n|solwora}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:bi:Crowley:2004|page=17}}\n\n{{C|bi|Salt}}\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ca-IPA|ò}}<!-- all five etyms, per GDLC and DNV -->\n* {{audio|ca|LL-Q7026 (cat)-Unjoanqualsevol-sol.wav|a=Catalonia}}\n* {{homophones|ca|sòl}}\n* {{rhymes|ca|ɔl|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|ca|roa-oca|sol}}, from {{inh|ca|la|sol|sōlem|sun}}, ultimately from {{inh|ca|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥}}.\n\n====Proper noun====\n{{ca-proper noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|astronomy}} the [[Sun]] (the center of our [[solar system]])\n\n====Noun====\n{{ca-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|astronomy}} [[sun]]\n# {{lb|ca|numismatics}} {{l|en|sol}} (a unit of currency used in Peru)\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|ca\n|posta de sol\n|ressol\n|sol coronat\n|sol ixent\n|sol ponent\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ca|solar}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{ca-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|music}} {{l|en|sol}} (the fifth note of the [[diatonic scale]])\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{bor+|ca|en|sol}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ca-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|ca|chemistry}} {{l|en|sol}} (a [[colloid]] suspension of a solid in a liquid)\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{inh+|ca|la|sōlus||solitary}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{ca-adj}}\n\n# [[alone]] ([[by oneself]], [[solitary]])\n#* {{quote-journal|ca|journal=Time Out Barcelona|date=March 12 2020|volume=588|column=Fight!|author=María José Gómez|page=8\n|passage=M'encanta viure en parella, sortir en grup, treballar en equip. Però també m'agrada estar '''sola'''.\n|t=I love living as a couple, going out in a group, working on a team. But I also like being '''alone'''.\n|url=https://digitalarchive.timeout.com/Europe/Spain/Barcelona/2020/March/TOB_588/DVL/reader.html}}\n# [[unique]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|ca\n|a soles\n|sol com un mussol\n|sol i vern\n|solament\n|solet\n|tot sol\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|ca|soledat}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|ca|verb forms}}\n\n# {{ca-verb form of|soler}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ca:IEC2}}\n* {{R:ca:DCVB}}\n\n{{C|ca|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Chavacano==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|cbk|es|sol||sun}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{cbk-IPA}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{cbk-noun}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n==Crimean Tatar==\n\n===Noun===\n{{crh-noun}}\n\n# [[left]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{crh-latin-noun|nıñ|ğa|nı|da|dan}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|crh|adjectives}}\n\n# [[left]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Useinov-Mireev 2002}}\n\n==Czech==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|cs|verb forms}}\n\n# {{infl of|cs|solit||2|s|impr}}\n\n==Danish==\n{{wp|da:}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|da|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|da|gmq-oda|sol}}, from {{inh|da|non|sól}}, from {{inh|da|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|/soːl/|[soːˀl]}}\n* {{rhymes|da|oːl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|en|e}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{da-noun-infl|en|e}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|da|verb forms}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|sole||imp}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|da|la|solutio|solūtiō|solution}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|/soːl/|[soːˀl]}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|en|er}}\n\n# {{lb|da|chemistry}} {{l|en|sol}} (solution)\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{da-noun-infl|en|er}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{der|da|la|solve|sol(ve)}} in the hymn for [[John the Baptist|St. John the Baptist]].\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|/sɔl/|[sʌl]}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|et|er|stem=soll}}\n\n# {{lb|da|music}} {{l|en|sol}} (note)\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{da-noun-infl|et|er|stem=soll}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:Den Danske Ordbog}}\n\n{{C|da|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|nl|la|solve|sol(ve)}} in the hymn for [[John the Baptist|St. John the Baptist]] all note names were taken from.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/sɔl/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-sol.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nl-noun|f|-en|+}}\n\n# {{lb|nl|music|Belgium}} {{l|en|sol}} (the fifth step in the [[solfège]] scale of C, preceded by [[fa]] and followed by [[la]])\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nl|solseutel}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|nl|los}}\n\n==Franco-Provençal==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n{{col-top|2|alt}}\n* {{alt|frp|souz||objl}}\n* {{alt|frp|cho|seul||brs}}\n* {{alt|frp|cheul||frb}}\n* {{alt|frp|soul||pms}}\n* {{alt|frp|seul||vld}}\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|frp|la|sōlus}}.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{frp-adj}} {{tlb|frp|orbl}}\n\n# [[alone]]\n\n====Notes====\nIn many areas replaced with its own derivative {{m|frp|solèt}}.\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|frp|solament}}\n* {{l|frp|solèt}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:frp:DFP|seul}}\n* {{R:frp:LTA|31281}}\n\n===Further information===\n* {{R:roa:ALF|76}}\n* {{R:FEW|12|78|sōlus}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|la:solum<t:soil, ground, floor>}}\nFrom {{bor|fr|la|solum||soil, ground, floor}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-Paris--sol.ogg|a=Paris}}\n* {{rhymes|fr|ɔl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# [[soil]], [[earth]]\n# [[ground]]\n# [[floor]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|fr\n|clouer au sol\n|hors-sol\n|sous-sol\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|fr|la|solve|sol(ve)}} in the [[hymn]] for [[John the Baptist|St. John the Baptist]] where all note names were taken from.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-Paris--sol.ogg|a=Paris}}\n* {{rhymes|fr|ɔl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m|#}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|music}} {{l|en|sol}} (the fifth step (G) in the [[solfège]] scale of C, preceded by [[fa]] and followed by [[la]])\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|fr|clef de sol}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{bor|fr|es|sol||sun}}, itself from {{der|fr|la|sol}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-Paris--sol.ogg|a=Paris}}\n* {{rhymes|fr|ɔl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# a Spanish-American gold or silver [[coin]], now the main currency unit of [[Peru]] ''(also '''new sol''')'', or a coin of this value\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{root|fr|ine-pro|*solh₂-}}\nFrom {{der|fr|la|solidus}}, a Roman coin. This form kept the historical spelling based on the Old French and Latin. See the main entry at {{m|fr|sou}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{fr-IPA|sou}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|archaic}} [[sou]] (the feudal era coin)\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n==Galician==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|gl|roa-opt|sol}}, from {{inh|gl|la|sol|sōl|sun}}, ultimately from {{inh|gl|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{gl-pr|sôl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{gl-noun|m}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n# [[sunlight]]\n# [[sunny]] [[side]] (of a place)\n#: {{ux|gl|quítate do '''sol'''|go away from '''sunny side'''|inline=1}}\n# [[daylight]] (the time between [[sunrise]] and [[sunset]])\n\n=====Antonyms=====\n* {{as|sunlight}} {{l|gl|sombra}}\n* {{as|sunny side}} {{l|gl|sombra}}\n* {{as|daylight}} {{l|gl|noite}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|gl|asollar|soán|solaina|solar|solario|soleado|solleiro|solloso|solpor}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{gl-pr|sôl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{gl-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|gl|music}} {{l|en|sol}} (a musical note)\n# {{lb|gl|music}} [[G]] (the musical note or key)\n\n====See also====\n{{list:musical solfège notes/gl}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{bor|gl|en|sol}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{gl-pr|sòl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{gl-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|gl|chemistry}} {{l|en|sol}} (a [[colloid]] suspension of a solid in a liquid)\n\n===References===\n* {{R:roa-opt:DDGM}}\n* {{R:gl:DDLG}}\n* {{R:TLPGP}}\n* {{R:gl:DRAG}}\n\n{{C|gl|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Guinea-Bissau Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|pov|pt|sol}}. Cognate with {{cog|kea|sol}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|pov|nouns}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n==Hausa==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ha-IPA|sOl}}\n\n===Ideophone===\n{{ha-pos|ideophone|sol}}\n\n# very [[white]]\n#: {{syn|ha|fat}}\n\n==Indonesian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{id-pr|sòl}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{bor|id|nl|zool}}, from {{der|id|dum|sole}}, from {{der|id|la-vul|sola}} (\"bottom of the shoe\", also \"flatfish\"), from {{der|id|la|solea||sandal, bottom of the shoe}}, from {{der|id|ine-pro|*swol-||sole}}. Compare to {{cog|af|sool}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{id-noun}}\n\n# [[sole]] (the bottom of a shoe or boot)\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col5|id\n|bersol\n|mengesol\n|mengesolkan\n|pengesol\n|pengesolan\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{bor|id|nl|sol}}, the first {{glossary|syllable}} of {{der|id|la|solve||to remove, get rid of}}, the first word of the fifth line, third verse (“Solve polluti, labii reatum”, that is, “Clean the guilt from our stained lips”) of the famed medieval hymn ''[[w:Ut queant laxis|Ut queant laxis]]'', which [[solfège]] was based on because its lines started on each note of the scale successively.\n\n====Noun====\n{{id-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|id|music}} {{l|en|sol}}:\n## in a movable-do or tonic sol-fa system: the fifth step in a scale, preceded by fa and followed by la\n## in a fixed-do system: the musical note G\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:KBBI Daring}}\n\n==Interlingua==\n\n===Noun===\n{{ia-noun|es}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n===Adjective===\n{{ia-adj}}\n\n# [[alone]]\n\n===Determiner===\n{{head|ia|determiners}}\n\n# {{lb|ia|quantifying}} [[only]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ia|solmente}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{wp|it:+ (nota)}}\nFrom the first syllable of {{der|it|la|solve}}, from the medieval hymn {{w|Ut queant laxis}}, from which the names of the notes were derived.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|sòl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{it-noun|m|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a musical note)\n# [[G]] (the musical note and key)\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|it|id=colloid|:bor|en:sol}}\nBorrowed from {{bor|it|en|sol}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|sòl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{it-noun|m|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a type of colloid)\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{ety|it|id=currency|:bor|es:sol}}\nBorrowed from {{bor|it|es|sol}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|sòl}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{it-noun|m|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a currency of Peru)\n# {{lb|it|historical}} {{l|en|sol}} (a former [[Spanish America|Spanish-American]] silver coin)\n\n===Etymology 4===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|sól}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{it-noun|m|apoc=1}}\n\n# {{apocopic form of|it|sole}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|sól}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{it-adj|apoc=1}}\n\n# {{apocopic form of|it|solo}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{it-adv|apoc=1}}\n\n# {{apocopic form of|it|solo}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:it:Treccani|sense=1}}\n* {{R:it:Treccani|sense=2}}\n* {{R:it:DiPI}}\n\n==Kabuverdianu==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|kea|pt|sol}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|kea|verbs}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n==Ladino==\n\n===Noun===\n{{lad-noun|g=m|heb=סול}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n{{topics|lad|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Latin==\n{{wp|la:}}\n[[Image:C solarcorona2003.gif|thumb|Sol [[oriens#Latin|oriens]].]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|la|Sōl}}\n* {{alt|la|☉||alchemy}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|la|id=sun|:inh|ine-pro:*sóh₂wl̥}}\nFrom {{inh|la|itc-pro||*s(u)wōl}}, from {{inh|la|ine-pro||*suh₂ṓl (*suh₂ól-s) ~ *suh₂l-és|t=the sun|g=m}}, rebuilt ''s''-stem from {{m|ine-pro||*súh₂el ~ *suh₂éns|g=n}} (whence {{cog|sa|स्वर् |t=the sun}}), leveled from {{m|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥}} ~ {{m|ine-pro||*suh₂éns}} (from {{m|ine-pro||*sh₂wéns}} via laryngeal metathesis).<ref>{{R:ine:Sihler:1995|page=84|section=88.3c|passage=*suHel}}</ref> Alternatively from {{inh|la|itc-pro||*saul}} through an irregular change conditioned by ''-l'', from {{inh|la|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥|*séh₂ul}}.<ref>{{R:itc:EDL|sōl, sōlis|570}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{la-IPA|sōl}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{la-noun|sōl<3>|g=m}}\n\n# {{lb|la|astronomy|often|capitalized}} the [[Sun]]\n# {{lb|la|astronomy}} a [[sun]]\n# {{lb|la|alchemy|chemistry}} [[gold]]\n# {{lb|la|figurative|in the plural}} [[day]]s, [[period]] of one's [[life]]\n#* {{Q|la|Catullus|Carmina|5|4–6|quote='''Soles''' occidere et redire possunt / nobis cum semel occidit brevis lux / nox est perpetua una dormienda|t='''Suns''' can set and rise again / but once this brief light ends / there is endless night for us to sleep.}}\n#* {{Q|la|Catullus|Carmina|8|3|thru=5|quote=Fulsere quondam candidi tibi '''soles''' / cum ventitabas quo puella ducebat / amata nobis quantum amabitur nulla.|t=Once shined for you beautiful '''suns''' / when you went where the girl led you / loved by us like no other [girl].}}\n# {{lb|la|mythology|nocat=1}} {{def-see|la|Sōl}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{la-ndecl|sōl<3>}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|la|sōlāris}}\n* {{l|la|sōlārium}}\n* {{l|la-vul|*sōliculum}} {{q|Vulgar}}\n\n====Descendants====\n{{top2}}\n* Insular Romance:\n** {{desc|sc|sole|sobi|soi|soli}}\n* Balkano-Romance:\n** {{desc|rup|soari}}\n** {{desc|ruo|sore}}\n** {{desc|ruq|soari}}\n** {{desc|ro|soare}}\n* Italo-Dalmatian:\n** {{desc|co|soli}}\n*** {{desc|sdn|soli}}\n*** {{desc|sdc|sori}}\n** {{desc|dlm|saul}}\n** {{desc|ist|sul}}\n** {{desc|it|sole}}\n** {{desc|itk|סוּלוֹ|tr=sulo}}\n** {{desc|nap|sole}}\n*** {{desc|roa-tar|sole}}\n** {{desc|scn|suli}}\n** {{desc|vec|sołe}}\n* Gallo-Italic:\n** {{desc|egl|såul|sôl|soul|saul}}\n** {{desc|lij|sô}}\n** {{desc|lmo|sol|so}}\n** {{desc|pms|sol|so}}\n** {{desc|rgn|sól}}\n* Gallo-Romance:\n** {{desc|roa-oca|sol}}\n*** {{desc|ca|sol}}\n** {{desc|pro|sol}} {{see desc}}\n* Ibero-Romance:\n** {{desc|an|sol}}\n** {{desc|mxi|שול}}\n** {{desc|roa-opt|sol}} {{see desc}}\n** {{desc|roa-ole|sol}}\n*** {{desc|ast|sol}}\n*** {{desc|ext|sol}}\n*** {{desc|roa-leo|sol}}\n*** {{desc|mwl|sol}}\n** {{desc|osp|sol}}\n*** {{desc|lad|sol//סול}}\n*** {{desc|es|sol}} {{see desc}}\n* Borrowings:\n** {{desc|en|sol|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|ia|sol|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|cel-bry-pro|*Sul|bor=1}}\n*** {{desc|kw|Sul}}\n*** {{desc|br|Sul}}\n*** {{desc|cy|Sul}}\n** {{desc|mul|{{taxfmt|Solaster|genus}}|der=1|lbor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:roa:AIS|si leva il sole|360}}\n* {{R:FEW|12|23|sōl}}\n* \"[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry=sol sol]\", in {{cite-book|author=Charlton T. Lewis and Charles Short|title=[[w:A Latin Dictionary|A Latin Dictionary]]|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|year=1879}}\n* \"[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0060:entry=sol sol]\", in {{cite-book|author=Charlton T. Lewis|title=An Elementary Latin Dictionary|publisher=Harper & Brothers|location=New York|year=1891}}\n* {{R:la:du Cange}}\n* {{R:la:Gaffiot}}\n<!--* {{R:M&A}}-->\n\n{{topics|la|Astronomy|Celestial bodies|Nature|Stars|Light sources}}\n\n==Lombard==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|lmo|la|sol|sōl}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|lmo|nouns}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n==Lower Sorbian==\n[[File:Jodsalz mit Fluor und Folsaeure.jpg|thumb|'''sol''']]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|dsb|sla-pro|*solь}}, from {{inh|dsb|ine-pro|*sḗh₂l}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|dsb|/sɔl/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{dsb-noun|f}}\n\n# [[salt]] {{gloss|sodium chloride}}\n# {{lb|dsb|chemistry}} [[salt]] {{gloss|a compound of an acid and a base}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{dsb-decl-noun-7|so|l}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|dsb|solny}}\n* {{l|dsb|solowy}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|enm|la|sol|sōl|sun}}, or perhaps from {{inh|enm|ang|sol|sōl|sun}}, both of which hail from {{inh|enm|ine-pro|*sóh₂wl̥}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{enm-noun|-}}\n\n# The [[bright]]est and [[warm]]est [[celestial body]], considered to be a [[planet]] in the [[w:Ptolemy|Ptolemic system]]; the [[Sun]] (the center of our [[solar system]]).\n# {{lb|enm|rare}} A heavy, yellow [[metal]]; [[gold]].\n#* '''c. 1395''' {{w|Geoffrey Chaucer}}, ''{{w|The Canterbury Tales}}''. Canon Yeoman's Prologue and Tale\n#*: {{quote|enm|Mercurie..and brymstoon..out of '''Sol''' and Luna were ydrawe.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{s|planet, metal}} {{l|enm|sonne}}\n* {{s|planet}} {{l|enm|Phebus}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry= sol |pos=n |id=MED33240|accessdate=17 June 2018}}\n\n{{C|enm|Metals|Planets|Stars|Sun}}\n\n==Northern Kurdish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|kmr|aii|ܨܘܠܬܐ}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{kmr-noun|f}}\n\n# [[shoe]]\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nb|/suːl/}}\n* {{IPA|nb|[suːɽ]|a=Many eastern and northern dialects}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|nb|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|nb|non|sól}}, from {{inh|nb|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nb-noun-c}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n#: {{ux|nb|'''Solen''' skinner.|t='''The sun''' is shining.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|nb\n|kveldssol\n|midnattssol\n|solbrent\n|solbrille\n|solbrun\n|solcelle\n|solemerke\n|solenergi\n|solfaktor\n|solfanger\n|solformørkelse\n|solhatt\n|solhverv\n|solkrem\n|solkysset\n|solnedgang\n|soloppgang\n|solrik\n|solsikke\n|solskinn\n|solskinnsdag\n|solskjerm\n|Solskjær\n|solslyng\n|solstikk\n|solstråle\n|solsystem\n|soltime\n|solur\n|solvarme\n|solvegg\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|nb|sole}} {{q|verb}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nShortened form of {{der|nb|la|solutio|solūtiō}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|nb|nouns|g=m}}\n\n# [[solution]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nb|aerosol}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nb|verb forms}}\n\n# {{infl of|nb|sole||imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n\n{{C|nb|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n{{wp|nn:+a}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n[[File:The_Sun_by_the_Atmospheric_Imaging_Assembly_of_NASA's_Solar_Dynamics_Observatory_-_20100819.jpg|thumb|''sola'']]\n{{dercat|nn|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|nn|non|sól}}, from {{inh|nn|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|nn|/suːl/|[suːl]}} {{nn-pronu-note}}\n* {{IPA|nn|[suːɽ]|a=Many eastern and northern dialects}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-f1}}\n\n# {{senseid|nn|sun}} [[sun]]\n#: {{ux|nn|'''Sola''' skin i dag.|t='''The sun''' shines today.}}\n# [[sunshine]]\n#: {{ux|nn|Det er '''sol''' ute.|t=There is '''sunshine''' outside.}}\n# a [[shining]]ly [[merry]] [[girl]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nn|sola}}, {{l|nn|sole}} {{q|verb}}\n{{col4|nn\n|bisol\n|det finst ingenting nytt under sola\n|gluggsol\n|ikkje la sola gå ned over vreiden sin\n|kveldssol\n|medsols\n|middelsol\n|midnattsol\n|morgonsol\n|motsols\n|plass i sola\n|rangsøles\n|rettsøles\n|skifte sol og vind\n|solauge\n|solbad\n|solbadar\n|solbakke\n|solbatteri\n|solblank\n|solblind\n|solblom\n|solbrend\n|solbrille\n|solbær\n|solcelle\n|soldis\n|soldogg\n|soldyrkar\n|soldyrking\n|soldøger\n|soldøgn\n|solefall\n|soleglad\n|soleie\n|soleklar\n|soleksem\n|solenergi\n|solfaktor\n|solfangar\n|solfaring\n|solfest\n|solfjerne\n|solflekk\n|solformørking\n|solgang\n|solgeisle\n|solglim\n|solglime\n|solgløtt\n|solhall\n|solhatt\n|solhjul\n|solhov\n|solhylle\n|solhøgd\n|solklar\n|solkomme\n|solkors\n|solkrem\n|solkross\n|solkverv\n|sollaus\n|solliv\n|sollys\n|solmei\n|solmerke\n|solmogen\n|solmørke\n|solmørking\n|solnedgang\n|soloppgang\n|solregn\n|solrenning\n|solrev\n|solrik\n|solsegl\n|solsetting\n|solside\n|solskin\n|solskive\n|solskjerm\n|solskugge\n|solsky\n|solslyng\n|solsmak\n|solsnu\n|solsprett\n|solspretting\n|solsteik\n|solstikk\n|solsting\n|solstorm\n|solstreif\n|solstråle\n|solsvidd\n|solsystem\n|soltak\n|soltid\n|soltilbedar\n|soltørk\n|soltørke\n|soltørking\n|solur\n|solvarm\n|solvarme\n|solveg\n|solvende\n|solvendel\n|solvending\n|solvind\n|solår\n|sommarsol\n|vêrsol\n|vintersol\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|nn|helio-}}\n* {{l|nn|solar}}\n* {{l|nn|solarium}}\n* {{l|nn|solsikke}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|nn|la|solve}}, from the first word of the fifth line of ''[[w:Ut queant laxis|Ut queant laxis]]'', the medieval hymn on which [[solfège]] was based because its lines started on each note of the scale successively. Through {{bor|nn|it|-}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|nn|so|id=solfège||an open syllable variant|}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|nn|/sɔːl/}} {{nn-pronu-note}}\n* {{homophones|nn|sål}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-m1|sol-}}\n\n# {{senseid|nn|solfège}} {{lb|nn|music}} {{l|en|sol|id=solfège}} (a syllable used in [[solfège]] to represent the fifth note of a [[major scale]])\n\n=====Coordinate terms=====\n* {{s|scale of solfège}} ''{{l|nn|do|id=solfège}}, {{l|nn|re|id=solfège}}, {{l|nn|mi|id=solfège}}, {{l|nn|fa|id=solfège}}, sol, {{l|nn|la|id=solfège}}, {{l|nn|ti|id=solfège}}, {{l|nn|do|id=solfège}}''\n\n===Etymology 3===\nShortened form of {{der|nn|la|solutio|solūtiō}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|nn|nouns|g=m}}\n\n# [[solution]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nn|aerosol}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom {{bor|nn|es|sol||sun}}, from {{der|nn|la|sol|sōl|sun}}, but also from {{der|nn|la|solidus}}. This makes it a {{doublet|nocap=1|nn|sold|sou|solid|solidus}}, as well as Norwegian {{l|nn|sol||g=f|sun|id=sun}} (Etymology 1).\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun|m|solen|soles|solane}}\n\n# {{senseid|nn|Peruvian money}} {{l|en|sol}}; the main [[Peru]]vian [[currency]] since 1991\n#* {{quote-journal|nn|date=4 September 2009|newspaper=w:Dag og Tid|page=11|passage=Det representerer investeringar på 4600 millionar '''soles''' [om lag 9 milliardar NOK], presiserer viseministeren.|translation=It represents investments of 4600 million '''sols''' [about 9 billion Norwegian kroner], says the vice minister.}}\n# {{senseid|nn|Peruvian money}} {{lb|nn|historical}} the Peruvian currency between 1863 and 1985\n#* {{quote-book|nn|year=1981|author=Gregorio Condori Mamani|translator=Svanaug Steinnes|title=Indianarliv i Peru|location=Oslo|publisher=Samlaget|page=48|passage=Alt dette kosta åtte '''soles'''.|translation=It cost eight '''sols''' in total.}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-n1}}\n\n# {{alt sp|nn|sòl}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n* {{R:nn:NO}}\n* {{R:no:Aasen}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a=los|los|lós|lòs|sol|sòl|sol-|Sol|slo}}\n\n{{C|nn|Celestial bodies|Sun|Currencies}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|ang|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*sōl}}, from {{inh|ang|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ang-IPA|sōl}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|oːl|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{ang-noun|?|head=sōl}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n# the [[Sun]]\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The exact gender is unknown. Based on cognates in related languages, it is speculated to be either feminine or neuter.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n{{col4|ang\n|siġel\n|sunne\n|sweġel\n|sweġl\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|ang|gmw-pro|*sol}}, from {{inh|ang|gem-pro|*sulą||mud, spot}}, from {{der|ang|ine-pro|*sūl-||thick liquid}}. Cognate with {{cog|goh|sol}}, {{m|goh|gisol||pool of excrement}}, {{cog|dum|sol||puddle, dirt, filth}}. More at {{l|en|soil}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{ang-IPA|sol}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|ol|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{ang-noun|n}}\n\n# {{senseid|ang|mud}} [[mud]], wet [[sand]], [[mire]]\n# wallowing-place, [[slough]], miry-place\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ang-decl-noun-a-n|sol|short=1}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col5|ang\n|solian\n|solmonaþ\n|solu\n|sylu\n|sylen\n|sylian\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|enm|sol|sole}} {{gl|merged with descendant of {{m+|ang|solu}}}}\n** {{desc|en|soil|soal}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{ang-adj}}\n\n# [[dark]], [[dirty]], [[soiled]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ang-adecl|sol}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|enm|sol|sole}}\n\n{{topics|ang|Sun}}\n{{topics|ang|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|fro|la|sōlus}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|fro|seul|soul|sul}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|fro|/ˈsou̯l/}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{fro-adj}}\n\n# [[alone]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|fro|solement}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|fr|seul}}\n* {{desc|en|sole|bor=1}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|fro|ine-pro|*solh₂-}}\n{{inh+|fro|la|solidus}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|fro|/ˈsɔl/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{fro-noun|m}}\n\n# [[#English|sol]] (an Old French coin)\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|fr|sou}}\n* {{desc|en|sol|bor=1}}\n\n==Old Galician-Portuguese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|roa-opt|/ˈsɔl/}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|roa-opt|la|solus|sōlus|alone}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|roa-opt|adverbs}}\n\n# [[only]]; [[just]]; no more than\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|roa-opt\n|sol non\n|sol que\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|roa-opt|soo}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{dercat|roa-opt|itc-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\nFrom {{inh|roa-opt|la|sol|sōl, sōlem|sun}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{roa-opt-noun|m}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n#* {{roa-opt-cite-cantigas|To|423|http://www.pbm.com/~lindahl/cantigas/facsimiles/To/bob095small.gif}}\n#*: Eſta primeira é de comel fez ó çeo. ⁊ á terra. ⁊ ó mar ⁊ o '''ſol'''. ⁊ á lũa. ⁊ as eſtrelas ⁊ todalas outras couſas q̇ ſon. ⁊ como fez ó ome áſa ſemellança\n#*:: This first one is (about) how He made the heaven, and the earth, and the sea, and the '''sun''', and the moon, and the stars, and everything else that exists. And how (He) made man in His own likeness.\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|fax|sol}}\n* {{desc|gl|sol}}\n* {{desc|pt|sol}} {{see desc}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|roa-opt|verb forms}}\n\n# {{inflection of|roa-opt|soer||3|s|pres|indc}}\n\n{{topics|roa-opt|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Old Occitan==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|pro|la|sol|sōl}}.\n\n===Proper noun===\n{{head|pro|proper noun|g=m}}\n\n# [[Sun]] (celestial object)\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|pro|solelh}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|oc|sol|qq=Florac, Lastic, Creuse}}\n* Old {{desc|oc-gas|só}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:FEW|12|23|title=sōl}}\n\n==Old Swedish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|gmq-osw|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|gmq-osw|non|sól}}, from {{inh|gmq-osw|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|gmq-osw|nouns|g=f|head=sōl}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{gmq-osw-decl-noun-o-f|sōl|dat_sg=sōlu}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|sv|sol}}\n\n==Piedmontese==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|pms|la|sol|sōl}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|pms|/sul/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|pms|nouns|g=m}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA|sól}}\n* {{audio|pt|LL-Q5146 (por)-Santamarcanda-sol.wav|a=<<Portugal>> (<<Porto>>)}}\n* {{rhymes|pt|ɔw<a:Brazil>|ɔl<a:Portugal>|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|pt|Sol}}\n* {{hyphenation|pt|sol}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|pt|itc-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\n{{inh+|pt|roa-opt|sol}}, from {{inh|pt|la|sol|sōl|sun}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# [[sun]]; [[sunlight]], [[sunshine]] {{gl|the light and heat which are received from the sun}}\n#: {{uxi|pt|O '''sol''' está quente hoje.|The '''sun''' is really hot today.}}\n#: {{uxi|pt|Não há nada melhor do que sentir o '''sol''' na pele.|Nothing beats feeling the '''sun''' on your skin.}}\n# {{lb|pt|figurative}} [[sun]] {{gl|a day}}\n# {{lb|pt|astronomy}} [[sun]] {{gl|a star, especially one at the center of a solar system}}\n# {{senseid|pt|weather}} {{lb|pt|uncountable}} [[weather]] {{gl|the state of the atmosphere at a specific time and place}} {{rfd-sense|pt}}\n#: {{ux|pt|O '''sol''' frio de inverno.|Winter's cold '''weather'''.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nThe uppercase spelling {{m|pt||Sol}} is used when referring to the astronomical object at the center of the [[solar system]] and in expressions such as {{m|pt||luz do Sol}}. See that entry for more.<ref>“[https://ciberduvidas.iscte-iul.pt/consultorio/perguntas/sol-com-maiuscula-e-sol-com-minuscula/32509 ''Sol'' com maiúscula e ''sol'' com minúscula]” in ''{{w|Ciberdúvidas da Língua Portuguesa|lang=pt}}'' (in Portuguese)</ref>\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|pt|solzinho,solinho<pos:diminutive>|solzão,solão<pos:augmentative>}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|pov|sol}}\n* {{desc|kea|sol}}\n* {{desc|pap|sol}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{uder|pt|la|solve}} in the hymn for [[John the Baptist|St. John the Baptist]].\n\n====Noun====\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a musical note)\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{bor+|pt|en|sol}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{pt-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|pt|chemistry|physics}} {{l|en|sol}} (a [[colloid]] suspension of a solid in a liquid)\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pt:Aulete}}\n* {{R:pt:DLP-ACL}}\n* {{R:pt:Infopédia}}\n* {{R:pt:Michaelis}}\n* {{R:pt:Priberam}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{bor|ro|la|solum||base, bottom; soil}}, {{bor|ro|fr|sol}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|n|soluri}}\n\n# the [[lowest]] part of something; [[bottom]], [[ground]], [[base]], [[foundation]], [[bed]]\n# the [[floor]] or [[pavement]] of a [[room]]\n# [[ground]], [[earth]], [[land]], [[soil]]\n# {{lb|ro|gymnastics}} an [[event]] performed on a floor-like carpeted surface\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-n-uri}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|ro|sla-pro|*sъlъ}}, compare {{cog|sl|sel}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{ro-noun|m|soli}}\n\n# [[messenger]]\n# [[envoy]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{ro-noun-m}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:DEX}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{s|Bosnian, Montenegrin, Serbian}} {{l|sh|so|sȏ}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|sh|ine-bsl-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\nFrom {{inh|sh|sla-pro|*solь}}. Compare {{m|sh|solyanka|t=type of Russian and Ukrainian soup}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|sh|/sôːl/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sh-noun|sȏl|f}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|Croatia}} [[salt]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|[[so]], [[sol]]|soli\n|soli|soli\n|soli|solima\n|sol|soli\n|soli|soli\n|soli|solima\n|[[solju]], [[soli]]|solima\n}}\n\n==Slovene==\n{{wp|sl:}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|sl|ine-bsl-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\nFrom {{inh|sl|sla-pro|*solь}}. {{etydate|16th century}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sl-IPA|sọ̑ł}}\n* {{audio|sl|LL-Q9063 (slv)-Zupanurska-sol.wav}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sl-noun|sọ̑ł|f}}\n\n# [[salt]] (a common substance)\n\n====Declension====\n{{sl-decl-noun-f-i-mobile|sól}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{R:sl:FR}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr|+<audio:LL-Q1321 (spa)-Rodelar-sol.wav<a:Spain>><audio:LL-Q1321 (spa)-Guergana-sol.wav<a:Germany>>}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{dercat|es|itc-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\n{{inh+|es|la|sol|sōl|sun}}. The Peruvian currency makes reference to the meaning \"sun\", but is a shortening from {{der|es|la|solidus}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n# [[sunlight]]\n# [[sunny]] [[side]] (of a place)\n#: {{ant|es|sombra}}\n#: {{uxi|es|quítate del '''sol'''|translation=get out of the '''sun'''}}\n# [[daylight]] (the time between [[sunrise]] and [[sunset]])\n#: {{ant|es|noche}}\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a unit of currency, currently used in Peru)\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|es\n|a la caída del sol\n|anteojos de sol\n|asolar\n|asolear\n|clave de sol\n|de sol a sol\n|gafas de sol\n|hacer brindis al sol\n|mijo del sol\n|parasol\n|perca sol\n|puesta de sol\n|reloj de sol\n|rocío del sol\n|sacar los trapitos al sol\n|salga el sol por Antequera\n|salga el sol por donde quiera\n|ser un sol|Sol de Mayo\n|solana\n|soleado\n|sol de justicia\n|sol y sombra\n|tendido de sol\n|tomar el sol,tomar sol\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|es|solar|solárium}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|cbk|sol|t=sun|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|en|sol#Etymology_3|t=currency|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|fr|sol#Etymology_3_4|t=currency|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|it|sol#Etymology_3_6|t=currency|bor=1}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|es|la|solve}} in the hymn for [[John the Baptist|St. John the Baptist]].\n\n====Noun====\n{{es-noun|m|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|sol}} (a musical note)\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{bor+|es|en|sol}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|es|chemistry}} {{l|en|sol}} (a [[colloid]] suspension of a solid in a liquid)\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|es|a=los|los}}\n\n{{C|es|Currency}}\n{{cln|es|3-letter words}}\n\n==Swedish==\n{{wp|sv:}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|sv|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{inh|sv|gmq-osw|sol|sōl}}, from {{inh|sv|non|sól}}, from {{inh|sv|gem-pro|*sōl|t=sun}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|sv|/suːl/}}\n* {{audio|sv|Sv-sol.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sv-noun|c}}\n\n# {{lb|sv|often in the definite singular}} [[sun]] (star the Earth revolves around)\n#: {{ux|sv|jorden kretsar kring '''solen'''|the Earth revolves around '''the sun'''}}\n# a [[sun]] (star, especially when seen as the center of a solar system)\n#: {{syn|sv|stjärna}}\n# [[sun]] (sunshine)\n#: {{syn|sv|solsken}}\n# {{lb|sv|figuratively}} a [[sun]] ((person who is a) source of joy)\n#: {{ux|sv|'''solen''' i mitt liv|'''the sun''' of my life}}\n# {{lb|sv|music}} {{l|en|sol}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sv-infl-noun-c-ar}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|sv\n|aftonsol\n|bisol\n|höstsol\n|kvällssol\n|middsagssol\n|midnattssol<t:midnight sun>\n|morgonsol\n|sola<t:to sunbathe>\n|solarisk\n|solarium<t:solarium>\n|solarplexus\n|solbad\n|solbada\n|solbadare<t:sunbather>\n|solbadd\n|solbana\n|solbatteri\n|solbelyst\n|solbestrålning\n|solblank\n|solblekt\n|solblind\n|solbländad\n|solblänk\n|solbrillor\n|solbrynt\n|solbränd\n|solbränna<t:sunburn, suntan>\n|solcell<t:solar cell>\n|solchans\n|solcykel\n|soldag\n|soldis\n|soldriven\n|soldrucken\n|soldräkt\n|soldränkt\n|soldyrkan\n|soldyrkare\n|soldäck\n|soleksem\n|solenergi\n|solfattig\n|solfjäder<t:fan>\n|solflimmer\n|solfläck\n|solflöde\n|solfångare<t:solar thermal collector>\n|solförmörkelse<t:solar eclipse>\n|solgass\n|solgassig\n|solgata\n|solglasögon<t:sunglasses>\n|solglimt\n|solglitter\n|solglänsande\n|solgud\n|solgul\n|solgård\n|solhatt\n|solhet\n|solhetta\n|solhjul\n|solhjälm\n|solhöjd\n|solig<t:sunny>\n|solinstrålning\n|solkanon\n|solkatt\n|solklar\n|solklänning\n|solkraft\n|solkräm\n|solkult\n|solkurva\n|solliv\n|solljus<t:sunlight; sun>\n|sollös\n|solmogen\n|solmättad\n|solnedgång<t:sunset>\n|solning\n|sol och vår\n|solochvåra\n|sol-och-våra\n|solochvårare\n|sol-och-vårare\n|solochvårman\n|sol-och-vår-man\n|sololja\n|solpanel\n|solparasoll\n|solreflex\n|solregn\n|solros<t:sunflower>\n|solrök\n|solsemester\n|solsida\n|solsken\n|solskiva\n|solskott\n|solskydd\n|solsnibb\n|solstek\n|solstekt\n|solsting\n|solstol\n|solstrimma\n|solstråle<t:ray of sunlight>\n|solstrålning\n|solstånd\n|solsystem<t:solar system>\n|solsäng\n|soltak\n|soltempel\n|solterrass\n|soltimma\n|soltimme\n|soltorka\n|soltorkning\n|soltält\n|soltörstande\n|soluppgång<t:sunrise>\n|solur\n|solvarg\n|solvarm\n|solvarv\n|solventil\n|solvind<t:solar wind>\n|solvisare\n|solvända\n|solvärmd\n|solvärme\n|solår\n|solöga\n|sommarsolstånd\n|vädersol\n|vintersolstånd\n}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sv|gassa}}\n* {{l|sv|lysa}}\n* {{l|sv|skina}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:svenska.se|so}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saol}}\n* {{R:svenska.se|saob}}\n* {{R:runeberg.org|svetym|0909.html sol}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|sv|a=los|los}}\n\n==Talysh==\n\n===Etymology===\nCognate with {{cog|fa|سال|tr=sāl}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tly|noun}}\n\n# [[year]]\n\n{{C|tly|Periodic occurrences}}\n\n==Tok Pisin==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|tpi|en|shoulder}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|tpi|nouns}}\n\n# {{lb|tpi|anatomy}} [[shoulder]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{der|tpi|en|salt}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|tpi|nouns}}\n\n# [[salt]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|tpi\n|solmarasin<t:Epsom salts>\n|solwara<t:sea, ocean; saltwater, brine>\n}}\n\n{{C|tpi|Seasonings}}\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|tr|ota|صول||tr=sol|left}}, from {{inh|tr|trk-pro|*sōl}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|tr|[soɫ]}}\n* {{hyphenation|tr|sol}}\n* {{audio|tr|96-sol.wav}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{tr-adj}}\n\n# [[left]] (side)\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tr-pred-c-adj|u|d}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{tr-noun|u|lar}}\n\n# [[left]] (side)\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tr-infl-noun-c|u|poss=1|pred=1}}\n\n=====Antonyms=====\n* {{l|tr|sağ}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|tr|verb forms}}\n\n# {{tr-verb form of|solmak}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{bor|tr|fr|sol}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|tr|[sol]}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{tr-noun|ü|ler}}\n\n# {{lb|tr|music}} [[#English|sol]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{tr-infl-noun-c|ü}}\n\n{{cln|tr|heteronyms}}\n\n==Veps==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|vep|urj-fin-pro|*soola}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|vep|nouns}}\n\n# [[salt]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{vep-decl-kuva|n=sg|sola}}\n\n==Volapük==\n\n===Noun===\n{{vo-noun}}\n\n# [[sun]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{vo-decl-noun}}\n\n{{topics|vo|Celestial bodies}}\n\n==Zazaki==\n\n===Etymology===\nUltimately from {{inh|zza|ine-pro|*sḗh₂l||salt}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{zza-noun}}\n\n# [[salt]]\n\n{{C|zza|Seasonings}}"}}